column1: Which major stock exchange index among the four "Asian Tiger" economies will perform best between 10 January 2019 and 28 June 2019?
column5: ["Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index", "Singapore's Straits Times Index", "South Korea's KOSPI", "Taiwan's Stock Exchange Weighted Index"]
column6: ['Finance', 'Foreign Policy']
column11: Hong Kong, Singapore, South Korea, and Taiwan have become known as the four "Asian Tigers" (iDeals Virtual Data Room, South China Morning Post, Investopedia). Outcome will be determined using data from Bloomberg, by dividing the end-of-day closing values for 28 June 2019 by the end-of-day closing values for 10 January 2019, which were: Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index (Bloomberg): 26,521.43 Singapore's Straits Times Index (Bloomberg): 3,183.51 South Korea's KOSPI (Bloomberg): 2,063.28 Taiwan's Stock Exchange Weighted Index (Bloomberg): 9,720.69 Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

Everything is bouncing around because of the US-China talks and Foxconn haven't made any friends this week: exposure to heavy mechanisation companies and chip-fabs presses on Korea and Taiwan, because in recessions, they go first (heavy capex). All are very, very dependent on China so a victory could be pyrrhic, but if China feels the need to turn more 'China first' then Hong Kong is where it will look.

The behaviour of financial markets is effectively random. I've spent a lot of time poring back through old North American index data and have found very little correlation, short term or long term, between information and signal. This forecast will be easy to update as time goes by and the deadline approaches. As I write this prediction, Hang Seng is down a little more than the other three (the day I make the guess), but this is just noise (which we will witness on all time scales).
south korea most oversold relative to value and less political risk versus Taiwan. hong king real estate market could really take a dive and singapore not cheap
Base case is that higher risk will provide higher returns. HK hang seng index has the highest beta of all four and therefore gets the highest weight.

Established the base rate(s) using the following method: 1) retrieved historical closing values for the indices on the dates mentioned in the question, 1998 to 2018 (plus minus one day if a no trading day in that year) 2) determined ratio and counted years that each index 'won'
Singapore is least likely to be impacted by world political affairs & to benefit from moves away from investment in China under tariffs.

Lots of geopolitical risk here, and a lot depends on the China-US trade talks. Chinese stocks are depressed as of today, taking commodities markets with them (I should know, i have some 'copper') and there are more serious shivers than usual over Taiwan, although sabre rattling has been going on for 60 years. Korea and Taiwan are highly dependent on automation and electronics groups selling into the USA so sensitive to any new US tariffs, while Korea also has major logistics companies shipping stuff from China. Singapore is a small index for companies wanting an offshore jurisdiction in Asia (the country itself only has 6 million people). The Hang Seng benefits from being the 'offshore' for big PRC companies and some Taiwanese groups that don't want to list in Taipei (which is very small). I am assuming there will be little real news coming out of the talks by mid year, although there may be a relief rally on the back of some cheerful-sounding PR newsbites. A bit of a 'pop' because of China-facing news, and some opportunity for a tech-related 'pop' in Korea.
Singapore is a strong economy that could benefit from a flight to safety in the event of rising trade tensions. Hong Kong & Taiwan are too linked to China.
Solution in trade war between US and China will benefit Taiwan the most, followed by Hang Seng.
